  "response_text": "The mean reserve biomass follows a distinct three-phase trajectory across 100 timesteps. Starting at approximately 90,000 units, biomass declines steadily over the first 30 timesteps, reaching a low of ~79,000 units by timestep 40. This early depletion phase corresponds to initial overstocking driven by agents' risk-averse stocking decisions (risk-att-init = 0.5) and absence of grazing restrictions (resting? = False). The subsequent recovery phase, achieving 127,000 units by timestep 70 through dynamic adjustments in livestock management strategies, reflects agents' learning-by-doing mechanisms (enabled by extension-model?) balancing grazing pressure with vegetation regrowth at the modified grass growth rate gr2 = 0.1. Final stabilization at ~123,000 units from timesteps 85-100 suggests achieved equilibrium between climate variability (rain-mean = 200, rain-std = 100) and proactive resource management incorporating satisficing trials (satisficing-trials = 21). The analysis reveals behavioral types' interaction with environmental uncertainty, demonstrating how agent adaptations to precipitation patterns shape long-term sustainability outcomes in this simulated common property grazing system."
